nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  
  nn <-   
    FNN::get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
  
  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint)
  
  return(output)  
}

Modes <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  tab <- tabulate(match(x, ux))
  ux[tab == max(tab)]
}

Introduction

Belgiums rail network, largely developed in the XIXth century, is one of the densest in the world. It is a central element of the Belgian mobility menu and the government plays an important role in promoting the use through a variety of policies and subsidies. Students and elderly citizens are encouraged to travel in off-peak times and public employees benefit from free or subsidized travel, and demand is high for this critical service in the densely populated European country. In recent years theres been mounting concern about the state of infrastructure and the safety and reliability of the network. Public subsidies mean there is significant pressure to ensure the efficient use of funds and provision of reliable, safe, comfortable services to the users. As a result, this old network has substantial maintenance needs.

Use Case

We propose an occupancy prediction model that feeds a tool or application to assist operators and transportation planners in better planning the system maintenance operations, taking into account the forecasted occupancy levels. This app would aid in minimizing the amount and impact of necessary planned service restrictions and have additional value as a means of effective communication around planned maintenance. By integrating and processing information and showing it in a clear centralized manner, our app will provide clarity to operational staff who need to make important decisions on a daily basis.

The occupancy forecasting system can play a crucial role, allowing the National Railway Company of Belgium (NMBS/SNCB) and planning authorities to optimize scheduling around peak demand. This would improve service safety and reliability while improving operational and financial performance.

Objectives

Objectives include optimizing maintenance, lowering costs (in terms of lost revenue) and minimizing maintenance-related disruptions to improve operations and user experience. By optimizing maintenance schedules, the operator can reduce costs while improving passengers experience and satisfaction. Broader subsequent goals for this project include revenue-maximizing train schedules.

Methodology

Exploratory analysis of the spatial and temporal data (geographic and temporal distribution of infrastructure, demand, weather and population), to identify patterns and relationships among variables.

The Belgian system can be considered a multinodal network, with some stations concentrating higher proportions of trips. Greater station density and a higher number of possible connections were more clearly correlated to trip count and occupancy than population density.

Time series analysis revealed some unexpected fluctuations in occupancy and trip counts across the week, such as many low occupancy trips on Friday afternoons. Our engineered features also showed higher numbers of low occupancy trips during rush hour.

The Belgian system is a multinodal network, but some stations concentrate higher proportions of trips.

Data

This analysis uses the Kaggle datasets of train lines, schedules and their occupancy levels, and stations. Theres three possible levels of train occupancy (dependent variable): low, medium, and high.

We are also using:

  • Belgian weather data

  • Belgian census data

  • Punctuality data

  • Level crossings data

trains <- read.csv("D:/OneDrive - PennO365/Semester 3/PPA/PPA Final/Final Project/data/trains_train.csv") %>%
#trains <- read.csv("C:/Users/dmvil/Desktop/PPA/final_project/data/trains_train.csv") %>%
  mutate(from = as.numeric(as.character(from)),
         to = as.numeric(as.character(to)))



#trains[is.na(trains)] <- 0

trains <- trains %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(stations, station_id, avg_stop_times, name), by = c("from" = "station_id")) %>%
  st_sf() %>% 
  mutate(from.X = st_coordinates(.)[, 1], 
         from.Y = st_coordinates(.)[, 2]) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(stations, station_id, avg_stop_times), by = c("to" = "station_id")) %>%
  st_sf() %>% 
  mutate(to.X = st_coordinates(.)[, 1], 
         to.Y = st_coordinates(.)[, 2]) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  mutate(distance = sqrt((from.X - to.X)^2 + (from.Y - to.Y)^2),
         stop_times_from = avg_stop_times.x,
         stop_times_to = avg_stop_times.y) %>%
  dplyr::select(-avg_stop_times.x, -avg_stop_times.y) %>%
  arrange(-distance)  # Arrange the data by descending distance

# Modify factors and create new variables in the 'trains' dataset
trains$occupancy <- factor(trains$occupancy)
trains$occ2 <- relevel(trains$occupancy, ref = "low")  # Relevel the 'occ2' variable
trains$OD <- paste(trains$from, trains$to, sep = "-")  # Create a new variable 'OD' by concatenating 'from' and 'to'

trains$time <- parse_date_time(trains$time, '%I:%M:%S %p')  # Parse the 'time' variable as a date-time object
trains$time <- substr(trains$time, 12, 19)  # Extract the time component from the date-time object
trains$date_time <- as.POSIXct(paste(trains$date, trains$time), format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")  # Combine date and time into a new variable 'date_time'

# Further data manipulation and create new variables
trains <- 
  trains %>%
  mutate(veh = substr(vehicle, 1, 1),
         interval60 = floor_date(ymd_hms(date_time), unit = "hour"),
         interval15 = floor_date(ymd_hms(date_time), unit = "15 mins"),
         week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label = TRUE),
         veh = substr(vehicle, 1, 1),
         hour = as.numeric(substr(time, 1, 2)),
         weekend = ifelse(dotw == "Sat" | dotw == "Sun", 1, 0),
         mor.jam = ifelse(hour >= 6 & hour <= 10 & weekend == "0", 1, 0),
         eve.jam = ifelse(hour >= 15 & hour <= 19 & weekend == "0", 1, 0),
         hour = factor(hour),
         weekend = factor(weekend),
         from = factor(from),
         to = factor(to))

Exploratory Analysis

We looked at the data fro a range of perspectives, isolating different variables and exploring specific subsets of data. The plots below consider the different kinds of data (continuous and categorical variables) and the relationship between the variables. Variables that reveal clear patterns or greater contrasts across binary outcomes are more useful for the purpose of developing our model.

This project is fundamentally about the distribution of variables (occupancy, and indirectly maintenance need) in space and time. Therefore, the exploration of spatial and temporal dimensions and data, their distribution and interrelations, are at the core of this project.

Spatial Analysis

We looked at the spatial dimension first, considering occupancy in relation to origin-destination pairs. In this case it is important to distinguish that OD pair occupancy with line occupancy, as there may be more than one way for passengers to get from point A to point B. In other words, passengers may use different lines (or combinations of lines) to get from their origin to their destination, and this could eventually have important implications when assessing system redundancies, occupancy of lines, impact of service disruptions, and options for increased efficiency.

Occupancy by Stations

Beyond the Origin-Destination (O-D) pairs, the specific origin and destination stations significantly influence the occupancy levels of train trips. To delve into the relationship between trip occupancy and the origin or destination station in our dataset, we grouped the train dataset by the From and To stations, categorizing them into three occupancy levels. Our analysis revealed a substantial impact of both the origin and destination stations on trip occupancy, as depicted in the accompanying figure. Notably, trips departing from or heading to certain stations, such as 8821964 (Tielen), consistently exhibit low occupancy levels. This pattern is observed across several stations.

Furthermore, our investigation uncovered variations in the impact of stations as origins or destinations on trip occupancy. For instance, approximately 67% of trips departing from station 8831401 (Diest) experience high occupancy, while 70% of trips heading to the same station have low occupancy. This disparity emphasizes the diverse influence of stations on trip occupancy levels. Consequently, we have decided to incorporate all From and To stations into our model to comprehensively account for these variations in trip occupancy dynamics.

Occupancy by Lines

We considered the impact of the serving line, referred to as the vehicle in our dataset. Adopting a methodology similar to our previous approach, we grouped the data based on line type. Specifically, we focused on selecting lines where 80% of the trips belonged to low, medium, or high occupancy categories. Additionally, we imposed a criterion of more than 5 trips for a line to be included in our analysis. This strategic selection aims to avoid lines with too few trips, which might exhibit unusual characteristics that could adversely affect the model. By incorporating the serving line into our investigation, we aim to enhance the comprehensiveness of our understanding of factors influencing occupancy levels in train trips.

Temporal Analysis

We looked at the frequency of occupancy categories across a range of time scales:

  • by week: counted as week of the year to have a consistent way of identifying weeks across any month;

  • by day of the week: to identify tendencies between the week and weekend;

  • by hour of the day: to look at commuter patters and similar behavior;

  • by rush hour: to isolate effects of known high demand time windows.

Feature Engineeering

In the process of feature engineering, our aim is to investigate the interplay among different stations. We have centered our inquiries on several key questions:

  1. Impact of Nearby Stations: How does the presence of neighboring stations influence the occupancy of a particular station?
  2. Significance of Station Density: Will the density of stations in a specific area emerge as a crucial factor in occupancy prediction?
  3. Proximity to High Density Settlements: Is there a correlation between proximity to major population centers, such as Brussels, and higher station occupancy?
  4. Temporal Lags: Is there a discernible pattern or time lag effect in the relationship between historical station data and current occupancy levels?

Spatial Process

The next step is to look at areas around each station. Were counting how many other stations are within a certain distance. To make it easier to use this information in our model, were grouping these counts into different levels. This helps us better understand and use the impact of nearby stations on our predictions.

trains$occupancy <- ordered(trains$occupancy,levels=c("low","medium","high") )

stations_d <-
  stations %>%
  dplyr::select(geometry) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  st_transform(31370) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  st_transform(st_crs(stations))

stations$station.Buffer =
  stations%>%
  st_buffer(26400) %>%
  aggregate(mutate(stations_d, station.Buffer = 1),., sum) %>%
  pull(station.Buffer)

stations <-

    station.Buffer <20 ~ "<20",
    station.Buffer >=20 & station.Buffer <40 ~ "20-40",

    station.Buffer >= 80 & station.Buffer < 100 ~ "80-100",
    station.Buffer >= 100 & station.Buffer < 120 ~ "100-120",
    station.Buffer >= 120 & station.Buffer < 140 ~ "120-140",
  ))

                 station_buffer_cat = stations$station_buffer_cat[match(trains$to, stations$station_id)],
                 avg_stop_time = stations$avg_stop_time[match(trains$to, stations$station_id)])


trains <-
  trains %>%

                        hour(interval60) >= 7 & hour(interval60) < 10 ~ "AM Rush",
                        hour(interval60) >= 10 & hour(interval60) < 15 ~ "Mid-Day",
                        hour(interval60) >= 15 & hour(interval60) <= 18 ~ "PM Rush"))

In the process of preparing our data for predicting train occupancy, were looking at how nearby train stations and the time of day might impact the number of people on trains. This involved categorizing station activity across various time segments, including peak morning and evening periods. Subsequently, we established spatial zones around each station, employing a geospatial approach to quantify the proximity of neighboring stations. This spatial analysis aimed to discern whether higher station density in the vicinity correlates with increased ridership. Furthermore, we incorporated a temporal dimension by categorizing train trips into distinct time-of-day periods, specifically during morning rush, mid-day, and evening rush hours. To refine our understanding, we leveraged the k-nearest neighbors function to identify the three nearest stations for each trip and ascertain their average distances. By doing this, were making sure our predictions account for factors like station density and distance, giving us a better understanding of what influences how crowded a train might be.

Temporal Process

In this temporal process of feature engineering, we investigate the correlation between time lags and train occupancy. The dataset is organized based on the origin station and the chronological order of intervals. Subsequently, lag features are created to capture the historical occupancy levels at various time intervals. These include lag features for the previous hour, 2 hours, 3 hours, 4 hours, 12 hours, 1 day, and 1 week. Each lag feature represents the occupancy level at a specific time in the past, allowing us to explore potential temporal dependencies in the data. The occupancy levels and lag features are then transformed into factors for categorical representation.

lagHour and occ2: There is a weak positive correlation (0.14) between the occupancy level of the current hour and the next hour. This means that if the occupancy is high in the current hour, there is a slight tendency for it to be higher in the next hour.

lag2Hours and occ2: There is a weak positive correlation (0.07) between the occupancy level of the current hour and the hour two hours later. This suggests a slight influence of the current occupancy on the occupancy two hours later.

There was negligible influence of any of the other lags. Based on this, we then checked for influence of 15 mins and 30 mins.

lag15min and occ2: The correlation coefficient of 0.14 suggests a weak positive correlation between the occupancy level in the current 15-minute interval and the occupancy level 15 minutes later. This implies that higher occupancy in the current 15-minute interval is associated with a slightly higher occupancy 15 minutes later.

lag30min and occ2: The correlation coefficient of 0.08 indicates a weak positive correlation between the occupancy level in the current 30-minute interval and the occupancy level 30 minutes later. Similar to the previous case, higher occupancy in the current 30-minute interval is weakly associated with a slightly higher occupancy 30 minutes later.

These correlations suggest a modest temporal dependence between the current occupancy level and future occupancy levels at 15-minute, 30-minute intervals, 1 hour and 2 hours.

Modeling

Methodology

For this project, we use Multinomial Logistic Regression as the modeling technique. The dependent variable encompasses three categories representing train occupancy levels: low, medium, and high.

  1. Variable Selection:
    • Various predictor variables were considered in the modeling process, including week, day of the week (dotw), vehicle (veh), hour, morning jam (mor.jam), evening jam (eve.jam), distance, from, to, stop_times_from, stop_times_to, lagHour, lag15min, station_buffer_cat, avg_stop_time, Temperature.x, Humidity.x, Wind_Speed.x, and time_of_day.
  2. Model Iterations:
    • Multiple iterations were performed by training several models (m1, m2, m3, m_all) with different combinations of predictor variables.
    • Additional features were engineered, including lag variables, station buffer categories, average stop time, and environmental factors.
  3. Stepwise Model Selection:
    • The stepwise model selection procedure (stepAIC) was applied to the comprehensive model (m_all) to iteratively choose a subset of predictor variables that optimized the models performance. This step helps prevent overfitting by selecting only relevant features.

We split the data into a 60-40 split, where 60% is the training set and 40% is the test set to check the accuracy of our predictions.

When predicting the occupancy level through multinomial logistic regression, the model calculates the probability for each occupancy level and ultimately selects the one with the highest likelihood as the predicted outcome.

For instance, in cases where the observed occupancy is high but the model predicts it as low, it implies that the calculated probability for low is higher than that for high, leading the model to classify the occupancy level as low.

# add 15 min lag
trains <- trains %>%
  arrange(from, interval60) %>%
  mutate(
    lag15min = lag(occ2, 1)
  )


trains <- 
  trains %>%
  mutate( mor.jam = factor(mor.jam),
        eve.jam = factor(eve.jam))

trains$veh <- as.factor(trains$veh)
trains$week <- as.factor(trains$week)

set.seed(123)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(
              y = paste(trains$occ2, trains$to, trains$veh_occ,  trains$OD_occ, trains$from, trains$dowt, p = .60),
              list = FALSE,
              times = 1)
yTrain <- trains[ trainIndex,]
yTest  <- trains[-trainIndex,]

yTrain$occ2 <- as.factor(yTrain$occ2)

m1 <- multinom(occ2 ~  week + dotw + veh + hour  + mor.jam + eve.jam + distance + from + to+ stop_times_from + stop_times_to, data = yTrain, MaxNWts =10000000)

m2 <- multinom(occ2 ~  week + dotw + veh + hour  + mor.jam + eve.jam + distance + from + to + stop_times_from + stop_times_to + lagHour + lag15min, data = yTrain, MaxNWts =10000000)

m3 <- multinom(occ2 ~  week + dotw + veh + hour  + mor.jam + eve.jam + distance + from + to + stop_times_from + stop_times_to + lagHour + lag15min + station_buffer_cat + avg_stop_time + time_of_day, data = yTrain, MaxNWts =10000000)

m_all <- multinom(occ2 ~  week + dotw + veh + hour  + mor.jam + eve.jam + distance + from + to + stop_times_from + stop_times_to + lagHour + lag15min + station_buffer_cat + avg_stop_time + Temperature + Humidity + Wind_Speed + time_of_day, data = yTrain, MaxNWts =10000000)

step.model <- stepAIC(m_all, direction = "backward", trace = TRUE)

Goodness of Fit

Cross Validation

The AUC (Area Under the Curve) value for model m3 is 0.6864. AUC is a metric commonly used to evaluate the performance of a classification model, particularly in the context of ROC curves. In this case, a higher AUC value indicates that the model m3 has a better ability to distinguish between the different classes (low, medium, and high occupancy levels) compared to a random classifier. An AUC of 0.5 suggests random performance, while an AUC of 1.0 indicates perfect discrimination.

With an AUC of 0.6864, the model m3 demonstrates a moderate to good discriminatory ability, suggesting that it performs reasonably well in predicting the occupancy levels across the three categories.

Cost Benefit Analysis

In a cost-benefit analysis (CBA) for occupancy predictions, especially when dealing with scenarios like predicting line closures, its essential to consider various factors beyond the accuracy metrics. Here are some key considerations:

1. False Positives and False Negatives:

  • False Positives (Type I Errors): Occur when the model predicts high occupancy, but the observed occupancy is low. This could result in unnecessary maintenance or service disruptions, incurring extra costs.

  • False Negatives (Type II Errors): Occur when the model predicts low occupancy, but the observed occupancy is high. This is particularly critical as it may lead to unplanned service disruptions, potentially impacting customer satisfaction and revenue.

2. Operational Impact:

  • Downtime Costs: Consider the costs associated with unnecessary downtime during maintenance due to false positives.

  • Service Disruption Costs: Assess the costs associated with service disruptions resulting from false negatives, including compensation to passengers, reputation damage, and potential revenue loss.

3. Maintenance Optimization: Calculate the potential cost savings achieved by optimizing maintenance schedules based on accurate predictions.

4. Customer Experience: Assess the impact of accurate predictions on customer satisfaction. A good prediction model can lead to fewer disruptions and improved overall experience.

5. Revenue Impact: Assess the potential revenue gain resulting from optimized schedules and improved service quality.

Based on this, we assume that the capacity of one train is 200 passengers and we assume that the cost of a ticket is 2.50 euro. We assume that incorectlyclosing a line would cause a loss of 500 euros in revenue.

testProbs_df <- as.data.frame(testProbs_m3)

train_capacity <- 200
ticket_cost <- 2.50
loss_revenue_per_closure <- 500

cost_benefit_table <- testProbs_df %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  count(Observe, Predict) %>%
  summarize(Low_Low = sum(n[Observe == 'low' & Predict == 'low']),
            Low_Medium = sum(n[Observe == 'low' & Predict == 'medium']),
            Low_High = sum(n[Observe == 'low' & Predict == 'high']),
            Medium_low = sum(n[Observe == 'medium' & Predict == 'low']),
            Medium_Medium = sum(n[Observe == 'medium' & Predict == 'medium']),
            Medium_High = sum(n[Observe == 'medium' & Predict == 'high']),
            High_Low = sum(n[Observe == 'high' & Predict == 'low']),
            High_Medium = sum(n[Observe == 'high' & Predict == 'medium']),
            High_High = sum(n[Observe == 'high' & Predict == 'high']),
            SUM = sum(n)
  ) %>%
  gather(Variable, Count) %>%
  mutate(Income =
           ifelse(Variable %in% c("Medium_Medium", "High_High"),
                  paste0(ticket_cost * train_capacity),
                  '0'
           ),
         Cost =
           ifelse(Variable %in% c("Low_High", "Medium_High", "High_Low"),
                  paste0('-', loss_revenue_per_closure),
                  '0'
           ),
         'Profits/per count' =
           ifelse(Variable %in% c("Medium_Medium", "High_High"),
                  paste0('-', ticket_cost * train_capacity),
                  '0'
           ),
         'Total_Profits' =
           ifelse(Variable %in% c("Medium_Medium", "High_High"),
                  Count * (ticket_cost * train_capacity),
                  '0'
           ),
         Description =
           case_when(
             Variable == "Low_Low" ~ "We predicted low demand with the low demand observation",
             Variable == "Low_Medium" ~ "We predicted low demand with the medium demand observation",
             Variable == "Low_High" ~ "We predicted low demand with the high demand observation",
             Variable == "Medium_low" ~ "We predicted medium demand with the low demand observation",
             Variable == "Medium_Medium" ~ "We predicted medium demand with the meidum demand observation",
             Variable == "Medium_High" ~ "We predicted medium demand with the high demand observation",
             Variable == "High_Low" ~ "We predicted high demand with the low demand observation",
             Variable == "High_Medium" ~ "We predicted high demand with the medium demand observation",
             Variable == "High_High" ~ "We predicted high demand with the high demand observation",
             Variable == "SUM" ~ "####"
           ),
         Observe_Predict = Variable
  )

cost_benefit_table$Total_Profits <- as.numeric(cost_benefit_table$Total_Profits)
cost_benefit_table$Total_Profits[cost_benefit_table$Observe_Predict == "SUM"] <- sum(cost_benefit_table$Total_Profits[1:9], na.rm = TRUE)

kable(cost_benefit_table,

Recommendations

Model Recommendation: The model demonstrates balanced performance across various metrics, indicating reasonable predictive capabilities. This balance is crucial for ensuring that the model provides accurate predictions across different occupancy levels, supporting effective maintenance planning.

  1. Trade-offs: For a maintenance planning application, the cost of false positives (unnecessary service restrictions) and false negatives (missed necessary maintenance) should be carefully considered. The trade-offs should align with the organizations operational goals and priorities.

  2. Use Case Alignment: The model aims to assist operators and transportation planners in better planning system maintenance operations. The moderate level of performance suggests that the model can be suitable for certain aspects of the use case. Its important to assess whether the models strengths align with the specific needs of the NMBS/SNCB in optimizing scheduling around peak demand and minimizing service restrictions.

  3. Continuous Improvement: Regular updates based on feedback, new data, and changing operational conditions can enhance the models effectiveness over time. This aligns with the goal of improving operational and financial performance.

The model appears to offer a reasonable level of performance for the NMBS/SNCBs maintenance use case. Its balanced performance, consideration of trade-offs, alignment with the use case, and emphasis on continuous improvement contribute to its suitability. However, ongoing monitoring and refinement are essential to ensure that the model continues to meet the specific needs and priorities of the NMBS/SNCB in optimizing maintenance planning and scheduling.

Key Considerations for Implementation:

  1. Goodness of Fit:

    • Emphasize Accuracy over Immediacy:

      • Fine-tune the model to prioritize accuracy even if it leads to a slight delay in predictions.

      • Adjust the model parameters to optimize for precision and recall, ensuring a balance that aligns with the importance of accurate predictions for maintenance planning.

  2. Nuanced Analysis & Profiling:

    • Customize Model for Stations and Lines:

      • Conduct a thorough analysis of station-specific and line-specific characteristics.

      • Customize the model or train station/line-specific models if significant variations are observed.

      • Consider clustering stations or lines with similar characteristics for more targeted and precise predictions.

  3. Variable Enrichment & Layering:

    • Progressive Inclusion of Variables:

      • Systematically include infrastructure and operational variables in the model, considering their impact on occupancy.

      • Start with core variables and progressively layer in additional features to identify their contribution to prediction accuracy.

      • Prioritize variables that have a significant impact on scheduling flexibility and maintenance priorities.

    • Evaluate Scheduling Flexibility:

      • Assess the impact of each variable on scheduling flexibility and prioritize those that provide actionable insights.

      • Consider variables related to track maintenance, train availability, and infrastructure condition to enhance the models understanding of scheduling constraints.

    • Dynamic Adjustment of Variables:

      • Implement a dynamic system that allows for the adjustment of variables based on real-time changes in infrastructure or operational conditions.

      • Regularly review and update the set of variables to ensure the model remains adaptive to the evolving transportation system.

These recommendations focus on aligning the model with the specific priorities of accuracy, nuanced analysis, and variable enrichment for the National Railway Company of Belgium (NMBS/SNCB). By customizing the model to the unique characteristics of stations and lines and progressively incorporating relevant variables, the model can provide more actionable insights for maintenance planning while maintaining a high level of accuracy.
